(TMCS, XRAY AND PROBE)
.break
.skip 3
.left margin 10
I.  PURPOSE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
This procedure defines the process by which TMCS, XRAY and PROBE are used
by Network Control.  A detailed description of TMCS, XRAY and PROBE and
their uses is documented in their appropriate manuals located on
Tymshare's System (NETDVDOC:33).
.nofill
.nojustify
(NETDVDOC:33) PROBE.DOC
(NETDVDOC:33) TMCS.DOC
(NETDVDOC:33) XRAY.DOC
.fill
.justify
.skip 2
.left margin 10
II.  DEFINITION
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
1.  PROBE:  PROBE is a utility package that resides on all Network
Supervisors.  It allows you to query all of the Network nodes, lines
and host interfaces and control some supervisor functions.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
2.  TMCS:  The Tymnet monitoring and control system is an inter-active
system which provide multiple users with selective access to the status
of the Tymnet Technology Network.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
3.  XRAY:  XRAY is an interactive monitoring and debugging system that
provides a real-time window into a Tymnet II node.  Through it, the
user can conveniently display information about the node's configuration,
performance and history.  Remember, this is only the local node.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
III.  PROCEDURE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
1.  PROBE:  Network Control should have at least five (5) terminals
logged into PROBE at all times.  One (l) should be logged into the
active Supervisor and the others should be logged into our standby
supervisors.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
.TEST PAGE 5
A.  The username "NETCON" will only be used by the pilot of the
Network.  All other PROBE terminals will be logged in using the
username of "NETCON2".  Remember, there should never be two (2) 
"NETCONS" logged into PROBE at the same time.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
B.  The standby terminals after being logged into PROBE,
and the printer turned on, should have an
"LOG S" command issued.  This command serves two purposes:
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
1.  It starts a logger by seconds on the active Supervisor.
.skip 1
.left margin 26
.indent -4
2.  It will give you the last time the inactive Supervisor went to
sleep.  Also, if the Sup had taken a crash, the time the crash occurred.
The inactive Supervisor paper log is also set to run in this mode, should
one of the inactive Supervisors start a Takeover.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
C.  The tasks that are most often performed by Network Control using
PROBE:
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.NOFILL
.nojustify
1.  Snapping nodes, hosts and lines
2.  Shutting/clearing lines
3.  All nodes list
4.  Sleeping/waking Supervisors
5.  RNODE
6. SYNPORT
7. DLOAD
8. Exceptions List (EXC)
9.  TSTAT
.left margin 21
10.  BORI and T2BORI
11.  Change Neighbors
12.  LSTMIN
13.  PERDAT
.fill
.justify
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
D.  A PROBE Manual is located in Network Control in a binder marked
"PROBE".  Also, each controller is required to have their own personal
copy of "PROBE" and they should be familiar with the commands within.
Any questions should be directed to the Shift Supervisor.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
2.  TMCS.  At the beginning of each shift, all Controllers are required
to make sure the required terminals in Network Control are logged into
TMCS and running properly.
.page
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
A.  The required programs used within Network Control:
.skip 1
.LEFT MARGIN 10
.NOFILL
.NOJUSTIFY
PROGRAM            USERNAME               USE
.skip 1
.LEFT MARGIN 10
HOST               NETCON3         MONITOR 24 HOUR HOSTS
COLORNODE          COLORNODE       MONITOR PUBLIC NODES & HOSTS
COLORLINE          COLORLINE       MONITOR LINES
COLORINFO          COLORINFO       NETWORK LOGIN INFORMATION
LOG                NETCON/NETCON 2 RUN A NETWORK LOG
DISPLAY            NETCON/NETCON 2 DISPLAY ALL NETWORK OUTAGES
GATEWAYS           GATEWAY       MONITOR PRIVATE NET GATEWAYS
.fill
.justify
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
B.  The primary systems used to run TMCS is Hosts 40l & 1400.  Both
systems should have identical databases.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
C.  A TMCS Manual is located in Network Control in a binder marked
"TMCS".  Also, each cntroller should have his own personal copy of
"TMCS" and they should be familiar with the commands within.  Any
questions should be directed to the Shift Supervisor. 
.page
list something
.page
list something
.page
.left margin 18
.indent -4
3.  XRAY:  XRAY provides a real-time window into a Tymnet II node.  
Through it, the user can conveniently display information about the node's
configuration, performance and history.  XRAY also has commands to monitor 
the status of a node's links, trace activity and isolate problems in
the node.  Last (and perhaps least) XRAY is a debugging tool for
programmers who can use it to diagnose nodecode and network bugs.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.INDENT -4
A.  Network control uses what is known as "REMOTE XRAY".  Remote access is
gained by remotely logging into the kernel host of a node that is up in the
network.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
B.  "ND" - Node Descriptor.  This is the primary command used within
Network Control. This command lets the controller find out more, in
less time, about a node configuration and current status in the node than
he could through any number of PROBE< TMCS and DDT (De-bugger) commands.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
C.  An "XRAY" manual is located in Network Control in a binder marked
"XRAY".  Also, each controller should have their own personal copy of
"XRAY".  They should be familiar with the commands within.  Any
questions should be directed to the Shift Supervisor.  
.page
