I.  PURPOSE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
This procedure defines the process by which an Ontyme message may be
sent out via Tymnet's Network.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
II.  DEFINITION
.skip 1
.left margin 18
Ontyme - Tymnet's electronic mail message switching service.  This
service allows messages to be sent and received on terminals.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
III.  PROCEDURE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
The considerations and procedures used to send out Ontyme messages are
detailed in the Ontyme Elementary Manual.  The current release of the
manual will be contained in a binder located in Network Control marked
"Ontyme Elementary Manual".
.skip 1
.left margin 18
When sending out Ontymes, a Network Controller will log in to the
system and always specify the date, time and who is to receive the
message.  The text should be clear and direct.  It should be constructed
in a professional manner.  The Ontyme should be signed with your Ontyme user
name.  See Example (1).
.skip 1
.left margin 18
Any time you use the Netcon user name, you must copy Netcon on the
Ontyme message.  When building files, private or public, use the
"Ontyme Elementary Manual" for a reference guide.
.page
.skip 3
.left margin 18
When sending an Ontyme to more than one person, you should use the
star files previouslyy created.  This is a list of the files with an
example of when to use them:
.skip 2
.left margin 22
.nofill
.nojustify
FILE               USE
.SKIP 1
.left margin 22
*Esculation        To send out esculation reports
*projects          To send out project summary
*Summary           To send out shift summary
*Trouble           To send out information to
                   maintenance regions
*FYI               To copy all Netcon personnel
**Supervisor       To send out supervisor information
.fill
.justify
.skip 2
.left margin 18
These files should be added to the bottom of a file build in editor.  You
then should run the program Ontyme - (R Ontyme).
