I.  PURPOSE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
This procedure defines the process by which a Dump may be performed
and how to perform a variety of dumps.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
II.  DEFINITION
.skip 1
.left margin 18
Dumps Node/slot - This is a release of all software in a node/slot to
be stored for examination at a later date.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
III.  PROCEDURE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
A.  Dumps should be performed on all nodes that drop out of the network.
This is accomplished by a program named Load II.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
1.  Each dump should have its own file name.  The file name will start
with the node name and end with DMP, and one character for the shift
(D,S,M) followed by the day of the month.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
2.  If you are unsure if there is a previous dump file on a particular
node, a directory (DIR/TOD) should be performed on 'NDxxx.*'.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
3.  If there is a previous dump file (ND267l.DMP), the next file should
be numbered (i.e. ND267l.DP1, ND267l.DP2, ND2671.DP3, etc.).  If you
name the file the same as a previous one, all previous information
will be cleared.  The new information would be written in place of the
previous information.
.skip 1
.left margin l8
NOTE:  At no time should a dump be dumped into any other directory then
Netcon's.
.page
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
B.  Only a 'C' dump should be performed on all nodes that are
available to perform a 'C' dump.  See example (1).  This dumps only
the crash table of a node, occupies minimal disc storage and utilizes
a minimum of c.p.u. time.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
1.  If the node is not able to be dumped through a 'C' dump, a 'D'
dump should be performed.  A 'D' dump dumps all of the software memory
in a node.  See example (2).
