SUPERVISOR CRASHES
.break
.skip 3
.left margin 10
I.  PURPOSE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
This procedure defines the process by which a Network Supervisor crash
is handled.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
II.  DEFINITION
.skip 1
.left margin 18
Supervisor Crash.  A Supervisor Crash can be defined as anytime a
Supervisor leaves the Network from a node or a Supervisor code crash.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
III.  PROCEDURE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
A.  ACTIVE SUPERVISOR CRASH.  When a Network Controller has determined
that the active Network Supervisor has failed or crashed, they should
take the following steps:
.skip 1
.left margin 18
1.  Check to see if the standby terminals are logged in and operational 
If they are, please awaken the Back-up Supervisor if no Sup has started
takeover.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
2.  After gaining control of the Network, log into the Supervisor that
has crashed, if possible.  Run a log back using the command in PROBE
(:LOG 5LS) to determine the nature of the crash.  This command will
give you the last 5 lines from the Supervisor prior to it crashing.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
3.  If it can be determined what caused the crash, then notify the
appropriate group.  Hardware problems are handled by the field engineering
group and software related problems should be reported to the NTD.  Note:
The NTD is not to be called after midnight, unless we're unable to get a
running supervisor.  All other problems will be reported to the Supervisor
Support Group the next morning.
.page
.skip 1
.left margin 18
4.  The following task must be performed after the Supervisor change
has been completed:
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.NOFILL
.nojustify
.nofill
.nojustify
a.  fill out a Netcon Incident Report.
b.  Fill out (Go SUPMOV) on System 25.
c.  Do an All Nodes (AN).
d.  Do a listing of the shuts (LSHUT).
e.  Send an Ontyme to the group file ** SUPERVISOR.
f.  Fill out Sup move form.
g.  Fill out Sup move log.
h.  Make copies of the Sup move form.  One copy goes to Network Control
manager, one copy goes with the shift turnover, the original copy is
placed in the Sup move book.
.fill
.justify
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
B.  INACTIVE SUPERVISOR CRASH.  An inactive Supervisor crash is handled
in the same fashion as an Active Supervisor, only you do not have to awaken
another supervisor.
.skip 1
.left margin l0
Network Operations is now responsible for publishing STATISTICS on the
operation of the supervisor.  In order to accomplish this successfully,
it will be necessary for us to improve the quality of information on our
supervisor incident reports.  With this in mind, please implement the
following policies with regard to the reporting of Supervisor problems:
.skip 1
.left margin 10
1.  A supervisor incident report should be completed anytime the supervisor is
moved.
.skip 1
.left margin 10
2.  A supervisor incident report should be completed anytime the active supervisor
fails to process log ins for two minutes or more.
.skip 1
.left margin 10
3.  Each supervisor incident report should be completed in its entirety with
as much information as possible.
.skip 1
.left margin 10
4.  A supervisor incident report should be completed anytime peak log in times
exceed 20 seconds and average log in times exceed l0 seconds for a duratin
of 3 minutes or more.
.skip 1
.left margin 10
5.  Any crashes of a supervisor machine should be logged.  This includes
crashes or inactive supervisors as well as the active supervisor.
