.CENTER 84
STANDBY NETWORK SUPERVISOR TERMINALS
.break
.skip 3
.left margin 10
I.  PURPOSE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
The procedure defines the way the standby Supervisors are utilized.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
II.  DEFINITION
.skip 1
.left margin 18
The standby Supervisors are five (5) terminals located within Network Control.
Each terminal will be logged into one of the Network Supervisors, via
PROBE>  One terminal will have an active Supervisor, the other terminals
will be logged into the other four (4) Supervisors in a "ready" state.
.skip 2
.left margin 10
III.  PROCEDURE
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
1.  The standby Network Supervisor terminals should be the first item
checked when starting turnover.  Each should be logged in via PROBE into
Hosts 121, 122, 123, 124 and 125.  The username will be "standby".  There
are three primary phone numbers used for accessing the Network, these
numbers are located on the side of the Supervisor 1 standby terminal.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
2.  Checking the standby terminals, you should verify that the terminal
is logged into the correct Host.  Check to see that the terminal has
a sufficient amount of paper.  Check and verify the "TIME", the (DF)
Drowiness Factor and the state of the standby supervisor.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
If a Supervisor is found to have a (DF) Drowiness factor other than
(0) zero, and/or in a state other than Active or Sleeping, should be noted in
the Network Control logbook.  Check wih the offgoing shift for the
current status on these Supervisors.  Also, a Network Control Incident 
ticket should be open until the problem is resolved.
.page
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
3.  A "LOG S" command will be issued on all standby Supervisors.  This will give
us a logger by seconds on the Active Supervisor.  On the other Supervisors,
we should get the last time that particular Supervisor went to sleep,
whether by command or otherwise.  Each terminal should be set to run on
hardcopy, except the Active Supervisor.  The purpose of the hardcopy is
to give a record of takeover, should the active Supervisor fail and a
standby Supervisor automatically starts taking over the Net.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
4.  If there is a problem with one of the terminals used for accessing
the standby Supervisors, another terminal within Network Control will be
designated as a standby terminal until the regular terminal is repaired.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
5.  Each standby terminal should be checked at least three (3) times during
each shift, not including turnover.
.skip 1
.left margin 18
.indent -4
6.  Problem with the standby Supervisors and terminals should be reported to
the appropriate people.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
A.  Being unable to log into a sleeping standby Supervisor should be reported
to the Manager of Network Control or designate, and NTD contacts.
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
B.  Ring No Answer (RNA) on our access numbers, should be reported to
Western Network Field Engineering (WNFE).
.skip 1
.left margin 22
.indent -4
C.  Terminal problems will be reported to Hewlitt-Packard for repair.
Any other problems will be reported to the shift Supervisor.
